            {
              "id": "glog-12390905-bc41-4793-958c-d4df0e105021",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "### Description\n\nThe \"Evaluate setTimeout for Untrusted Data\" vulnerability in JavaScript arises when the `setTimeout` function is used with a string argument that can be influenced by untrusted data. This can lead to code injection attacks, as the string is evaluated as JavaScript code. In the context of the provided code snippet, if `setTimeout` is used with a string that includes untrusted data, it could allow an attacker to execute arbitrary code.\n\n### General Mitigation Advice\n\n1. **Avoid String Arguments**: Always use function references or arrow functions instead of string arguments in `setTimeout`.\n2. **Input Validation**: Validate and sanitize any input that could be used in `setTimeout` to ensure it does not contain malicious code.\n3. **Content Security Policy (CSP)**: Implement CSP headers to restrict the execution of inline scripts and reduce the risk of code injection.\n4. **Use Libraries**: Consider using libraries that provide safer alternatives to `setTimeout` and other similar functions.\n\n### Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using a string argument, use a function reference or an arrow function:\n\n```javascript\nsetTimeout(() => { this.yieldBench() }, 1000);\n```\n\n### Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any additional library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n### Relevant Links\n\n- [OWASP Top Ten](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [CWE-95: Improper Neutralization of Directives in Dynamically Evaluated Code ('Eval Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/95.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DS172411"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "glog-d4684999-3b37-4ba7-a8de-ac63a9914752",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "### Description\n\nThe \"Assessment of Evaluation for Unreliable Data\" vulnerability in JavaScript arises when the `eval()` function is used to execute code that can be influenced by user input or other untrusted sources. This can lead to code injection attacks, where an attacker can execute arbitrary code within the context of the application, potentially leading to data theft, data corruption, or other malicious activities.\n\n### General Mitigation Advice\n\n1. **Avoid `eval()`**: The best way to mitigate this vulnerability is to avoid using `eval()` altogether. There are often safer alternatives to achieve the same functionality without executing code dynamically.\n\n2. **Use JSON Parsing**: If `eval()` is used to parse JSON, replace it with `JSON.parse()` which is safer and more efficient.\n\n3. **Sanitize Inputs**: If dynamic code execution is absolutely necessary, ensure that all inputs are properly sanitized and validated to prevent injection of malicious code.\n\n4. **Use a Secure JavaScript Engine**: Consider using a secure JavaScript engine or sandbox environment that restricts the execution of potentially harmful code.\n\n### Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the use of `eval()` with safer alternatives. For example, if `eval()` is used to parse JSON, use `JSON.parse()` instead.\n\n#### Vulnerable Code\n\n```javascript\n// Vulnerable code using eval\nlet userInput = \"{ 'key': 'value' }\";\nlet data = eval(userInput);\n```\n\n#### Fixed Code\n\n```javascript\n// Fixed code using JSON.parse\nlet userInput = '{ \"key\": \"value\" }';\nlet data;\n\ntry {\n    data = JSON.parse(userInput);\n} catch (e) {\n    console.error(\"Invalid JSON input\", e);\n}\n```\n\n### Library Dependencies\n\nThe above code example does not require any additional library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n### OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top Ten](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n\n### Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-95: Improper Neutralization of Directives in Dynamically Evaluated Code ('Eval Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/95.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DS189424"
                ]
              }
            },
